    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Chicago, Ill.</placeName>, <date>March 30,
                    1865</date></p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                <placeName>Philada.</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Annexed please find a communication<lb/> for the Occident.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In the last part of this communication a<lb/> topic is touched which
                might deserve<lb/> some earnest considerations from the Jewish<lb/> press. My
                remarks are in an ironical<lb/> strain, perhaps another contributor of your<lb/>
                periodical, or its chief editor, may deem it<lb/> proper to speak on it more
                earnestly and<lb/> thoroughly.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am, dear sir, in true regard</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Your obd't serv't</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">B. Felsenthal</persName>
            </p>
            <p>N. B. The word „sect,” occurring several times<lb/> in the annexed communication, has
                been made</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>use of with intention and purpose. I would<lb/> request you not to strike out this
                expression.<lb/> The truth indicated by this word (viz: that<lb/> Judaism in our
                days has divided into two sects).<lb/> I am ready to defend at any time. I<lb/> am
                well aware that many eminent men<lb/> in <placeName>Israel</placeName> will not
                consent to this assertion.<lb/> Still I am convinced of its truth-<lb/>fulness.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
